A Nautilus developer has stored confidential data on the jump host within Stratos DC. To ensure security and compliance, this data must be transferred to one of the app servers. Given developers lack direct access to these servers, the system admin team has been enlisted for assistance.

Copy /tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg file from jump server to App Server 1 placing it in the directory /home/web.

Secure File Transfer Task
1ï¸âƒ£ Task Understanding
ğŸ”¹ What is the task?

A confidential file stored on the Jump Server must be securely copied to Application Server 1 (stapp01) and placed in:

/home/web


File to copy:

/tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg

ğŸ”¹ Why is this required in a real-world enterprise?

In enterprise environments:

Developers do NOT have direct access to production servers

Sensitive data must not remain on jump/bastion hosts

Jump servers are temporary access points, not storage locations

Compliance (ISO, SOC2, PCI-DSS) requires least privilege & secure data handling

ğŸ‘‰ System Administrators act as controlled intermediaries to move data safely.

ğŸ”¹ Which servers does this apply to?
Server	Role	Why
Jump Server	Secure access gateway	Source of the confidential file
App Server 1 (stapp01)	Application Tier	Authorized destination
NAS / DB / LB	âŒ Not involved	No role in this task
2ï¸âƒ£ Prerequisites & Assumptions
ğŸ”¹ Required Access

SSH access to Jump Server

SSH access to App Server 1

Ability to write to /home/web
(either ownership or sudo access)

ğŸ”¹ Required Files & Services

File exists:

/tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg


SSH service running on both servers

Network connectivity between jump host and app server

ğŸ”¹ Important Checks Before Starting
ls -l /tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg


âœ” Confirms file exists
âœ” Confirms permissions
âœ” Confirms file size (sanity check)

3ï¸âƒ£ Exact Commands (Step-by-Step)

âœ… Production-safe approach: scp
(encrypted, audited, standard enterprise tool)

ğŸ”¹ Step 1: Login to Jump Server
ssh nautilus@jump-server


Explanation:

Establishes a secure SSH session

All transfers must originate from the jump host

Why this is best:

Jump server enforces audit logging

Direct access to app servers is restricted

ğŸ”¹ Step 2: Copy File to App Server 1
scp /tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg web@stapp01:/home/web/

Line-by-Line Explanation
Part	Meaning
scp	Secure Copy Protocol
/tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg	Source file
web@stapp01	Destination user & server
/home/web/	Target directory

Why this command is best:

Encrypted in transit (SSH)

No temporary files created

Widely approved in enterprise environments

Simple, auditable, reliable

ğŸ”¹ (Optional) If Permission Is Denied

Login to App Server and fix ownership:

ssh web@stapp01
sudo chown web:web /home/web

4ï¸âƒ£ Verification & Validation
ğŸ”¹ Verify on App Server 1
ssh web@stapp01
ls -l /home/web/nautilus.txt.gpg

âœ… Expected Output Example
-rw-r--r-- 1 web web 2048 Jan 19  nautilus.txt.gpg

ğŸ”¹ Verify File Integrity (Optional but Professional)

On jump server:

sha256sum /tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg


On app server:

sha256sum /home/web/nautilus.txt.gpg


âœ” Hashes must match

5ï¸âƒ£ Errors & Troubleshooting
âŒ Error: No such file or directory

Cause: File path incorrect
Fix:

ls -l /tmp/nautilus.txt.gpg

âŒ Error: Permission denied

Cause: No write access to /home/web
Fix:

sudo chown web:web /home/web

âŒ Error: Connection timed out

Cause: SSH blocked / network issue
Fix:

ping stapp01
ss -tlnp | grep ssh

6ï¸âƒ£ Security & Best Practices
ğŸ” Security Implications

.gpg file remains encrypted

Transfer happens over SSH

No exposure to unauthorized users

âœ… Why This Approach Is Recommended

Least privilege

No data duplication

No SCP alternatives with weaker security

Fully auditable

ğŸ”„ Alternatives (Enterprise Scenarios)
Method	When Used
